Background:

This data set is originally from the CDC, but I found a condensed and cleaned version on Kaggle. The data comes from the 2020 annual CDC survey data of about 400k adults related to their health status. There were 18 variables for a population of 319,795 individuals.

Variables included yes/no answers for the following: heart disease, smoking, alcohol drinking, stroke, difficulty walking, diabetic, physical activity, asthma, kidney disease, and skin cancer. It also included variables that were ranked on various scales for BMI, physical health, mental health, general health, and sleep time. Lastly included individuals sex, age range, and race.

Throughout my analysis I used the following variables: heart disease, smoking, diabetic, BMI, sleep time, sex, and age range.

It should be noted that for the sake of the analysis I assigned numeric values to the heart disease variable. For the entire analysis No heart disease is represented as a -1 and Yes heart disease is represented as a 1.

Overarching Question: Are certain variables indicative of the likelihood of having heart disease?

Questions:

1) What percentage of the population had heart disease?

2) Are males or females more likely to have heart disease?

3) Is age an indicator for how likely it is to have heart disease?

4) Are individuals with diabetes more likely to have heart disease than those without diabetes?

5) Are individuals that have ever smoked more likely to have heart disease than those that have never smoked?

6) How much more likely are individuals to have heart disease if they smoke and are diabetic?

7) Are individuals with an abnormal BMI more likely to have heart disease than those with a normal BMI?

8) Does an individuals average amount of sleep indicate their likelihood of having heart disease?

dat <- read_csv("Heart 2020 Cleaned - heart2020cleaned.csv")

Question 1: What percentage of the population had heart disease?

heart_desease <- dat %>%
  mutate(HeartDisease_Num =
           case_when(
             HeartDisease == 'No' ~ -1,
             HeartDisease == 'Yes' ~ 1))
  
heart_disease_tibble <- heart_desease %>%
  group_by(HeartDisease_Num) %>%
  summarise(number = sum(abs(HeartDisease_Num)), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  mutate(perc =  (number/sum(number))*100)
#27,373 = count of individuals with heart disease
heart_desease_plot <- heart_desease %>%
  group_by(HeartDisease_Num) %>%
  summarise(number = sum(abs(HeartDisease_Num)), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  mutate(perc =  (number/sum(number))*100) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=HeartDisease_Num, y=perc,label=round(perc, digits=2))) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  geom_text(position = position_dodge(width = .9),  
                             vjust = -0.5,   
                             size = 3) + 
  labs(x='-1 = No Heart Disease AND 1 = Heart Disease',
       y='Percentage of People',
       title='Percentage of People With Heart Disease',
       subtitle = 'Population: 319,795',
       caption= 'Source: CDC 2020 Annual Survey Data') +
  theme_bw()
heart_desease_plot

Answer 1: 8.56% of the 2022 population had heart disease which is 27,373 individuals.

Question 2: Are males or females more likely to have heart disease?

First I wanted to quickly see if there was an equal number of males and females in the data set.

sex_dist

There is, so then I continued answering my question.

sex_dat <- dat %>%
  mutate(HeartDisease_Num =
           case_when(
             HeartDisease == 'No' ~ -1,
             HeartDisease == 'Yes' ~ 1)) %>%
  filter(HeartDisease_Num == 1)

sex_dat_plot <- sex_dat %>%
  group_by(HeartDisease_Num, Sex) %>%
  summarise(number = sum(abs(HeartDisease_Num)), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  mutate(perc =  (number/sum(number))*100) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=HeartDisease_Num, y=perc, fill=Sex, label=round(perc, digits=2))) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  facet_wrap(~Sex) +
  geom_text(position = position_dodge(width = .9),  
                             vjust = -0.5,   
                             size = 3) + 
  labs(x='Heart Disease',
       y='Percentage of People',
       title='Females vs Males',
       subtitle = 'Population: 27,373',
       caption= 'Source: CDC 2020 Annual Survey Data') +
  theme_bw()
sex_dat_plot

Answer 2: 41.04% of the individuals with heart disease are females while 58.96 of the individuals with heart disease are males, so males are more likely to have heart disease than females.

Question 3: Is age an indicator for how likely it is to have heart disease?

I again wanted to check that there was a relatively even amount of data for each age range considering the full population of individuals in the data set.

dat_hist <- dat %>% 
  mutate(AgeCat =
           case_when(
             AgeCategory == '18-24' ~ 18,
             AgeCategory == '25-29' ~ 25,
             AgeCategory == '30-34' ~ 30,
             AgeCategory == '35-39' ~ 35,
             AgeCategory == '40-44' ~ 40,
             AgeCategory == '45-49' ~ 45,
             AgeCategory == '50-54' ~ 50,

             AgeCategory == '60-64' ~ 60,
             AgeCategory == '65-69' ~ 65,
             AgeCategory == '70-74' ~ 70,
             AgeCategory == '75-79' ~ 75,
             AgeCategory == '80 or older' ~ 80
            ))

hist(dat_hist$AgeCat, ylim = c(0,320000),  main = "Histogram of Age Category Distribution According to the Population")

Distribution was normal. 

age_plot <- dat %>%
  mutate(HeartDisease_Num =
           case_when(
             HeartDisease == 'No' ~ -1,
             HeartDisease == 'Yes' ~ 1)) %>%
  filter(HeartDisease_Num == '1') %>%
  group_by(HeartDisease_Num, AgeCategory, Sex) %>%
  summarise(number = sum(abs(HeartDisease_Num)), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=AgeCategory, y=number, label=number, fill=AgeCategory)) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~Sex) +
  labs(
    x = 'Age Category',
    y = 'Count of People',
    title = 'Age Category of Individuals With Heart Disease',
    subtitle = 'Population Size: 319,795',
    caption= 'Source: CDC 2020 Annual Survey Data') +
  theme_light() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))
age_plot

Answer 3: It is clear that age is an indicator of the likelihood of having heart disease. As one gets older they are more likely to have heart disease.

Question 7: Are individuals with an abnormal BMI more likely to have heart disease that those with a normal BMI?

Normal BMI includes BMIs between 18.5 and 24.9 while abnormal BMIs include BMIs 25 and higher. There were about a 100 BMIs that were under 18.5 that I did not include.

BMI_categories <- dat %>% 
    mutate(HeartDisease_Num =
           case_when(
             HeartDisease == 'No' ~ -1,
             HeartDisease == 'Yes' ~ 1)) %>%
  mutate(BMI_range =
           case_when(
             BMI >=25 ~ "Abnormal",
             BMI >= 18.5 & BMI <=24.9  ~ "Normal"))

BMI_normal <- BMI_categories %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  filter(BMI_range == 'Normal') %>%
  group_by(HeartDisease_Num, BMI_range) %>%
  summarise(number = sum(abs(HeartDisease_Num)), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  mutate(perc =  (number/sum(number))*100)

BMI_normal_plot <- ggplot(BMI_normal, aes(x=HeartDisease_Num, y=perc, label=round(perc, digits=2))) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  geom_text(position = position_dodge(width = .9),  
                             vjust = -0.5,   
                             size = 3) +
  labs(
    y = 'Percent of People',
    x = '-1 = No Heart Disease AND 1 = Heart Disease',
    title = 'Normal BMI',
    subtitle = 'What Percentage Have Heart Disease?',
    caption= 'Source: CDC 2020 Annual Survey Data') +
  theme_light() 
BMI_normal_plot

6.47% of indiviudals with a normal BMI have heart disease. 

BMI_abnormal <- BMI_categories %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  filter(BMI_range == 'Abnormal') %>%
  group_by(HeartDisease_Num, BMI_range) %>%
  summarise(number = sum(abs(HeartDisease_Num)), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  mutate(perc =  (number/sum(number))*100)

BMI_abnormal_plot <- ggplot(BMI_abnormal, aes(x=HeartDisease_Num, y=perc, label=round(perc, digits=2))) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  geom_text(position = position_dodge(width = .9),  
                             vjust = -0.5,   
                             size = 3) +

    x = '-1 = No Heart Disease AND 1 = Heart Disease',
    title = 'Abnormal BMI',
    subtitle = 'What Percentage Have Heart Disease?',
    caption= 'Source: CDC 2020 Annual Survey Data') +
  theme_light() 
BMI_abnormal_plot

9.51% of individuals with an abnormal (higher than normal) BMI have heart disease.

Answer 7: With 6.47% of individuals with a normal BMI having heart disease and 9.51% of individuals with an abnormal BMI having heart disease, it is about 50% more likely to have heart disease if you have an abnormal BMI.

Question 8: Does an individuals average amount of sleep indicate their likelihood of having heart disease?

sleep_table <- dat %>%
  mutate(HeartDisease_Num =
           case_when(
             HeartDisease == 'No' ~ -1,
             HeartDisease == 'Yes' ~ 1)) %>%
  filter(HeartDisease_Num == 1) %>%
  filter(SleepTime >= 5 & SleepTime <= 10) %>%
  group_by(HeartDisease_Num, SleepTime) %>%
  summarise(number = sum(abs(HeartDisease_Num)), .groups = 'drop')
datatable(sleep_table)

Answer 8: Not really

Conclusion:

There are certain variables that indicate an individuals likelihood of having heart disease including sex, age, whether or not they smoke and whether or not they have diabetes, or have diabetes and smoke. Specifically, males, older individuals, and individuals with a higher than normal BMI are more likely to have heart disease than females, young individuals, and those with normal BMIs. Additionally, individuals that smoke are 2x as likely to have heart disease than those that do not and individuals that are diabetic are 3x as likely to have heart disease than non-diabetics while individuals that are diabetic and smoke are 6x more likely to have heart disease than individuals that do not have diabetes and do not smoke. And sleep is not a variable that indicates an individuals likelihood of heart disease.
